        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-6">
          1. Why Vaughan's Rapid Growth Creates Basement Problems
        </h2>

        <div class="prose prose-slate max-w-none">
          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Vaughan's population exploded from 182,000 in 2001 to over 323,000 in 2021, making it one of Canada's fastest-growing cities. This 77% population surge triggered a construction boom that fundamentally changed how basements perform across the city. The rush to build tens of thousands of homes created systemic waterproofing problems that homeowners are discovering years after purchase.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Between 2015 and 2022, developers built approximately 45,000 new housing units in Vaughan. This unprecedented pace meant construction crews worked year-round, often in suboptimal conditions. Winter foundation pours, rushed inspections, and cost-cutting measures became standard practice. The result is a generation of homes with inadequate basement waterproofing that won't become apparent until heavy rainfall or spring snowmelt tests the systems.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-cyan-50 border-l-4 border-cyan-500 p-6 my-8 rounded-r-lg">
            <div class="flex items-start">
              <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-cyan-500 mr-3 flex-shrink-0 mt-1" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 16h-1v-4h-1m1-4h.01M21 12a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z" />
              </svg>
              <div>
                <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-cyan-900 mb-2">Growth Impact Reality</h3>
                <p class="text-cyan-800">
                  DrySpace tracks waterproofing failures across York Region. Vaughan homes built between 2015-2022 experience basement water issues at 3.4 times the rate of homes built before 2010. The correlation between rapid construction and poor waterproofing is undeniable.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            The Infrastructure Lag Problem
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Vaughan's stormwater infrastructure struggled to keep pace with development. New subdivisions added thousands of impermeable surfaces — roofs, driveways, roads — that concentrate runoff. When heavy rain hits, overwhelmed storm sewers back up into weeping tile systems connected to municipal drains. This reverse flow pushes water directly into your basement through foundation drainage systems designed to remove water, not receive it.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            The City of Vaughan's 2023 Stormwater Master Plan acknowledged capacity shortfalls in 68% of established drainage areas. Neighborhoods along Rutherford Road, Major Mackenzie Drive, and the Highway 7 corridor experience the most severe infrastructure deficits. Your basement pays the price when century-old drainage ditches meet modern subdivision runoff volumes.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            Soil Conditions Across Vaughan
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Vaughan sits on varied soil conditions that directly impact basement waterproofing performance. The western half, particularly Woodbridge and Maple, contains clay-rich soils deposited by ancient Lake Algonquin. These clay soils expand when wet and contract when dry, creating movement that cracks foundation walls and breaks waterproofing membranes.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Eastern Vaughan, including Thornhill and parts of Concord, features sandy loam soils that drain better but still create problems. Water moves quickly through sandy soil, accumulating against foundations without adequate drainage systems. Developers often skipped proper weeping tile installation in sandy areas, assuming natural drainage would suffice. It doesn't.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-slate-100 rounded-xl p-6 my-8">
            <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4">Vaughan Soil Profile by Area</h4>
            <div class="overflow-x-auto">
