      <!-- Section 2: Humber Flooding -->
      <section id="humber-flooding" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-20">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-6">
          2. Humber River & Woodbridge: Vaughan's Flood Zone
        </h2>

        <div class="prose prose-slate max-w-none">
          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            The Humber River defines Woodbridge's eastern boundary and creates unique basement waterproofing challenges that don't exist elsewhere in Vaughan. This 126-kilometer river drains a massive watershed that includes portions of Brampton, Bolton, and King Township. When heavy rain hits this catchment area, the Humber's flow increases rapidly, raising groundwater tables across Woodbridge and pushing water into basements miles from the river itself.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            The 2005 Flood Event: A Turning Point
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            January 2005 brought record rainfall to southern Ontario. The Humber River at Woodbridge reached 265 cubic meters per second, more than four times its normal winter flow. Over 200 Woodbridge homes experienced basement flooding, with water entering through foundation cracks, window wells, and overwhelmed sump pumps. The Toronto and Region Conservation Authority declared it a 100-year flood event.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Homes between Islington Avenue and Highway 27, particularly in the Kipling Avenue corridor and around Woodbridge Memorial Arena, took the worst damage. Groundwater levels rose 2.4 meters above normal, creating hydrostatic pressure that forced water through even minor foundation imperfections. Insurance claims exceeded $18 million across Woodbridge alone.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-500 p-6 my-8 rounded-r-lg">
            <div class="flex items-start">
              <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-amber-500 mr-3 flex-shrink-0 mt-1" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 9v2m0 4h.01m-6.938 4h13.856c1.54 0 2.502-1.667 1.732-3L13.732 4c-.77-1.333-2.694-1.333-3.464 0L3.34 16c-.77 1.333.192 3 1.732 3z" />
              </svg>
              <div>
                <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Flood Zone Reality</h3>
                <p class="text-amber-800">
                  If your Woodbridge home sits within 2 kilometers of the Humber River, you're in an elevated risk zone for groundwater-driven basement flooding. Standard interior waterproofing won't protect you during major flood events. Exterior drainage systems with proper grading and sump pump capacity are essential.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            2013: Another Wake-Up Call
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            July 2013 brought Toronto's most expensive storm event in history. Vaughan received 126mm of rain in less than two hours. The Humber River again overflowed, flooding Woodbridge basements that had been "waterproofed" after 2005. This second event proved that basic waterproofing measures don't address the fundamental problem: you're living in a flood plain with inadequate drainage infrastructure.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            The 2013 flood highlighted a critical issue with weeping tile connections. Many Woodbridge homes have foundation drains that connect to the municipal storm sewer system. During extreme rainfall, these sewers run at full capacity or overflow, sending water backward through weeping tiles directly into your foundation drainage system. This reverse flow bypasses exterior waterproofing entirely, entering through the intentional drainage paths around your foundation.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            High Water Table Areas in Woodbridge
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Even without major flooding, Woodbridge maintains elevated groundwater levels year-round due to proximity to the Humber River. Spring snowmelt and fall rains push the water table within 1-2 meters of the surface in low-lying areas. Homes along these streets experience chronic basement moisture issues:
          </p>

          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-slate-700 mb-6 ml-4">
            <li>Clarence Street between Islington Avenue and Kipling Avenue</li>
            <li>Pine Valley Drive south of Highway 7</li>
            <li>Cityview Boulevard near Boyd Conservation Area</li>
            <li>Ansley Grove Road and surrounding crescents</li>
            <li>Riverside Drive properties backing onto the Humber</li>
            <li>Wigwoss Drive and adjacent courts</li>
            <li>Valleyview Crescent and Valley Woods Court</li>
          </ul>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            If you live in these areas, your basement waterproofing strategy must account for constant hydrostatic pressure, not just occasional heavy rain. Interior drainage systems alone won't work. You need exterior waterproofing with aggressive drainage, possible installation of a drainage mat system, and redundant sump pump capacity with battery backup.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-slate-100 rounded-xl p-6 my-8">
            <h4 class="text-xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4">Humber River Flood Risk by Distance</h4>
            <div class="overflow-x-auto">
              <table class="min-w-full divide-y divide-slate-200">
                <thead>
                  <tr>
                    <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left text-sm font-semibold text-slate-900">Distance from River</th>
                    <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left text-sm font-semibold text-slate-900">Groundwater Impact</th>
                    <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left text-sm font-semibold text-slate-900">Flood Risk Level</th>
                    <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left text-sm font-semibold text-slate-900">Recommended Protection</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody class="divide-y divide-slate-200 bg-white">
                  <tr>
                    <td class="px-4 py-3 text-sm text-slate-700">0-500m</td>
