                    <td class="px-4 py-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Event-driven elevation</td>
                    <td class="px-4 py-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Moderate</td>
                    <td class="px-4 py-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Exterior waterproofing + proper drainage</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="px-4 py-3 text-sm text-slate-700">2km+</td>
                    <td class="px-4 py-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Minimal impact</td>
                    <td class="px-4 py-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Low</td>
                    <td class="px-4 py-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Standard waterproofing adequate</td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            Insurance Implications for Woodbridge Homes
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Many Woodbridge homeowners discovered their insurance policies excluded overland flooding coverage after the 2013 event. Standard home insurance covers sudden internal water damage like burst pipes but excludes flood damage from rising groundwater or overflowing rivers. After 2013, insurers began offering optional overland flood coverage, but premiums for Woodbridge properties near the Humber can exceed $2,000 annually with high deductibles.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            If you're buying a Woodbridge home near the Humber River flood plain, factor flood insurance into your budget. Better yet, invest in proper basement waterproofing that prevents flooding rather than just insuring against it. A $25,000 waterproofing investment that eliminates flood risk outperforms decades of insurance premiums and claim hassles.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3: Builder Defects -->
      <section id="builder-defects" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-20">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-6">
          3. Builder Defects: What Developers Didn't Get Right
        </h2>

        <div class="prose prose-slate max-w-none">
          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Vaughan's luxury home boom created a paradox: million-dollar homes with basement waterproofing that fails within five years. The construction frenzy between 2015-2022 prioritized speed and profit margins over quality. DrySpace has documented recurring defects across subdivisions built by major developers. These aren't random failures — they're predictable results of systemic cost-cutting.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            The Damp-Proofing Deception
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Most Vaughan homes built after 2015 received damp-proofing, not waterproofing. These terms sound similar but represent vastly different levels of protection. Damp-proofing is a spray-on asphalt coating that blocks moisture vapor but cannot withstand hydrostatic pressure. Waterproofing is a rubber-modified membrane, typically blue or orange, that creates a true water barrier capable of handling groundwater pressure.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Ontario Building Code allows damp-proofing in low-risk situations, and builders exploit this loophole to save $3,000-$5,000 per home. The result is predictable: when groundwater levels rise during spring melt or heavy rainfall, water penetrates the inadequate damp-proof coating and enters your basement through foundation pores. By the time you discover the leak, your Tarion warranty has often expired.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-red-50 border-l-4 border-red-500 p-6 my-8 rounded-r-lg">
            <div class="flex items-start">
              <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-red-500 mr-3 flex-shrink-0 mt-1" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M6 18L18 6M6 6l12 12" />
              </svg>
              <div>
                <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-red-900 mb-2">Damp-Proofing vs. Waterproofing</h3>
                <p class="text-red-800">
                  If your foundation exterior has a thin black coating, that's damp-proofing, not waterproofing. It will fail. True waterproofing is a thick, rubber-modified membrane in blue, orange, or white. When replacing defective damp-proofing, demand proper membrane waterproofing with 20+ year material warranties.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            Inadequate Weeping Tile Systems
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Weeping tiles (perforated drainage pipes) should surround your foundation at footing level, wrapped in filter fabric, and bedded in clear stone. This system collects groundwater and directs it away before pressure builds against foundation walls. In practice, Vaughan builders often installed cheap corrugated plastic pipe without fabric wrapping, used insufficient stone, or worse, skipped exterior weeping tiles entirely.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            DrySpace excavates 60-80 Vaughan foundations annually. Common weeping tile defects we document include pipe installed above the footing instead of beside it, gaps in pipe connections where water escapes, crushed pipes from improper backfill, and silt-clogged perforations from missing filter fabric. One Kleinburg luxury home had weeping tile installed in only 40% of the foundation perimeter — the builder simply stopped mid-installation.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            Grading Disasters: Water Flows Toward Your Home
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Proper lot grading creates a 6-inch drop over the first 10 feet away from your foundation. This simple slope directs surface water away from basement walls. Vaughan subdivisions built during the boom routinely feature reverse grading — lots that slope toward homes. After years of settling, roof runoff and yard drainage flows directly against your foundation, overwhelming waterproofing systems designed to handle groundwater, not concentrated surface flow.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Subdivisions with documented grading problems include Sonoma Heights, The Estates of Credit Ridge, and portions of Vellore Woods. Developers rushed final grading to meet occupancy deadlines, creating drainage problems that won't be apparent until after warranty expiration. Many Vaughan homeowners spend $8,000-$15,000 correcting builder grading mistakes — costs that should have been included in the original million-dollar purchase price.
          </p>

