                    <td class="px-4 py-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Submit Year 2 form 30-90 days before anniversary</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="px-4 py-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Years 3-7</td>
                    <td class="px-4 py-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Major Structural</td>
                    <td class="px-4 py-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Foundation defects causing water penetration</td>
                    <td class="px-4 py-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Submit warranty claim form immediately when discovered</td>
                  </tr>
                  <tr>
                    <td class="px-4 py-3 text-sm text-slate-700">After Year 7</td>
                    <td class="px-4 py-3 text-sm text-slate-700">None</td>
                    <td class="px-4 py-3 text-sm text-slate-700">No Tarion coverage</td>
                    <td class="px-4 py-3 text-sm text-slate-700">Homeowner responsible for all repairs</td>
                  </tr>
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            How to Document Waterproofing Issues
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Successful Tarion claims require thorough documentation. When you discover basement water issues, take timestamped photos showing the water source, extent of water damage, and any visible foundation cracks or defects. Measure the affected area. Note weather conditions — when did it rain, how much precipitation occurred, and how soon after rainfall did water appear.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Keep records of all communication with your builder. Send written notices describing problems, even if you also call. Document the builder's response or lack thereof. If the builder attempts repairs, photograph the work before, during, and after. If repairs fail, this documentation proves the original fix was inadequate, strengthening your case for comprehensive waterproofing rather than patch repairs.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            When Builders Refuse to Fix Problems
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Many Vaughan builders dispute warranty claims, arguing that water entry results from homeowner actions or isn't covered under Tarion guidelines. If your builder refuses to address documented waterproofing problems, you can escalate to Tarion's conciliation process. A Tarion inspector will visit your home and issue a binding decision about coverage and required repairs.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Tarion inspectors see hundreds of similar cases. They know common builder defects and standard excuses. A well-documented claim with photos, records of maintenance, and evidence of construction defects significantly improves your chances of a favorable decision. If Tarion rules in your favor but the builder still refuses repairs, Tarion may pay for the work directly and pursue reimbursement from the builder.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            Should You Wait for Tarion or Fix It Yourself?
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            This dilemma frustrates many Vaughan homeowners. Tarion processes take months or years. Your basement continues leaking while you wait for claim resolution. Water damage accumulates, creating mold risks and structural deterioration. The practical question becomes: can you live with ongoing water intrusion while pursuing warranty coverage?
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            If water entry is minor — occasional dampness, small amounts during heavy rain — documenting the issue and pursuing Tarion coverage makes sense. If you're experiencing significant water intrusion that threatens your home's structure or creates health hazards, fix it now. You can still pursue warranty claims after completing repairs, though Tarion will only reimburse costs if they determine the issue was covered. Don't let warranty processes delay essential repairs that protect your largest investment.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-amber-50 border-l-4 border-amber-500 p-6 my-8 rounded-r-lg">
            <div class="flex items-start">
              <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-amber-500 mr-3 flex-shrink-0 mt-1" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 8v4m0 4h.01M21 12a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z" />
              </svg>
              <div>
                <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Warranty Repair Reality</h3>
                <p class="text-amber-800">
                  Even when Tarion orders builders to fix waterproofing problems, builders often choose the cheapest solution that technically complies with the order. This means interior crack injection instead of exterior waterproofing, or minimal grading adjustments instead of comprehensive drainage solutions. Tarion orders may not deliver the quality waterproofing your home actually needs.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

