      <section id="neighborhood-challenges" class="mb-16 scroll-mt-20">
        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-6">
          5. Neighborhood-by-Neighborhood Challenges
        </h2>

        <div class="prose prose-slate max-w-none">
          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Vaughan's diverse neighborhoods face different basement waterproofing challenges based on age, soil conditions, elevation, and development patterns. Understanding your specific area's issues helps you choose appropriate waterproofing solutions and set realistic budget expectations. Here's what DrySpace has documented across Vaughan's major neighborhoods.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            Woodbridge (L4L, L4H): The Flood Risk Zone
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Woodbridge contains approximately 95 linear kilometers of foundation requiring waterproofing across its established neighborhoods. Proximity to the Humber River creates perpetual high water table conditions. Homes built in the 1960s-1980s along Islington Avenue, Highway 27, and the Kipling Avenue corridor typically have aging clay tile drainage systems that have collapsed or become clogged with sediment.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Newer Woodbridge subdivisions near Highway 7 and Rutherford Road suffer from rapid development issues — poor compaction, inadequate drainage infrastructure, and the damp-proofing problems described earlier. The combination of high water tables and construction shortcuts makes Woodbridge Vaughan's most challenging waterproofing environment. Budget $18,000-$32,000 for comprehensive exterior waterproofing in typical Woodbridge homes.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            Thornhill (L4J, L6A): Split Jurisdiction Complications
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Thornhill spans Vaughan and Markham, creating municipal jurisdiction confusion that affects waterproofing requirements and permit processes. Vaughan's portion of Thornhill includes approximately 78 linear kilometers of residential foundation. The area's sandy loam soils drain reasonably well but channel water rapidly toward foundations without proper weeping tile systems.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Thornhill's established neighborhoods along Bathurst Street and Dufferin Street contain homes from the 1970s-1990s with original waterproofing that has exceeded its design life. Basement finishing in these homes often covered early signs of moisture intrusion. When homeowners discover problems decades later, water damage has spread behind finished walls. Thornhill waterproofing projects average $14,000-$26,000 for exterior work plus potential interior restoration costs of $8,000-$25,000 if finished basements sustained water damage.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            Maple (L6A): Suburban Sprawl Challenges
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Maple contains roughly 62 linear kilometers of residential foundation across subdivisions built primarily between 1990-2015. The area's clay loam soils create moderate drainage challenges. Major Mackenzie Drive and Keele Street form Maple's main arteries, with sprawling subdivisions extending in all directions. Most homes feature standard builder-grade waterproofing from their construction era — adequate when installed but rarely maintained or upgraded.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Maple's waterproofing issues typically emerge 15-25 years after construction when original systems fail. Foundation settlement in clay soils creates cracks that bypass waterproofing membranes. Aging sump pumps fail during critical heavy rainfall events. Landscaping mature trees and shrubs establish root systems that damage drainage tiles. Maple homeowners should budget $12,000-$24,000 for preventive or reactive exterior waterproofing.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            Kleinburg (L0J): Luxury Homes, Standard Problems
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Kleinburg's approximately 34 linear kilometers of residential foundation includes some of Vaughan's most expensive homes. Properties in Kleinburg Crown Estates, The Estates at Credit Ridge, and along Nashville Road command premium prices but often feature the same waterproofing shortcuts as more modest homes. Heavy clay soils in Kleinburg create severe expansion and contraction cycles that stress foundation walls and waterproofing systems.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Kleinburg's luxury homes typically have deeper foundations, larger footprints, and more complex foundation geometries than standard homes. These factors increase waterproofing costs to $35,000-$55,000 for comprehensive exterior work. Kleinburg homeowners also demand premium finishes and minimal disruption, which adds 15-25% to project costs compared to similar work in other Vaughan neighborhoods.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            Concord (L4K): Mixed-Age Infrastructure
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Concord's approximately 48 linear kilometers of residential foundation spans decades of construction from 1980s townhomes to 2020s detached homes. Jane Street and Highway 7 intersection forms Concord's commercial core, surrounded by dense residential development. The neighborhood's mixed ages create varied waterproofing challenges — old townhome complexes need full exterior replacement, while newer homes require warranty defect corrections.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Concord's high density creates site access challenges for waterproofing projects. Narrow side yards, shared driveways, and proximity to neighbors' properties complicate excavation. Some Concord townhomes require interior waterproofing because exterior access is impossible. Budget $10,000-$22,000 for accessible foundation perimeters, or $8,000-$15,000 for interior-only solutions when exterior work isn't feasible.
          </p>

