          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            What's Included in Exterior Waterproofing
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Professional exterior waterproofing includes multiple components that work together to keep your basement dry. Excavation removes soil to expose the full foundation wall from grade to footing. Foundation preparation involves power-washing walls, repairing cracks, and creating a clean surface for membrane adhesion. The waterproofing membrane application typically uses modified bitumen or rubber-based products with 20-30 year material warranties.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Weeping tile installation places perforated 4-inch pipe at footing level, wrapped in filter fabric to prevent silt infiltration. Clear stone backfill around weeping tiles creates a drainage channel that directs water away from the foundation. Final backfill uses excavated soil, properly compacted in layers to prevent future settlement. Finish grading creates the critical slope away from your home that prevents surface water infiltration.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            Interior Waterproofing: The Cost-Effective Alternative
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Interior waterproofing manages water after it enters the foundation wall system but before it damages your basement space. This approach costs significantly less than exterior work but doesn't prevent water from contacting your foundation. Interior systems work well for minor moisture issues or situations where exterior access is impossible. However, they're not appropriate for homes with major structural water problems or high water tables.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Vaughan interior waterproofing costs range from $35 to $95 per linear foot, with most homes paying $3,500-$9,500 for complete perimeter systems. A basic interior drain tile and sump pump installation for a 100-foot perimeter averages $5,500-$7,500. Adding wall vapor barriers, floor crack repair, and upgraded sump systems increases costs to $8,000-$12,000. Interior solutions work best for Vaughan homes on well-drained soil with minor water intrusion during heavy rainfall only.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-cyan-50 border-l-4 border-cyan-500 p-6 my-8 rounded-r-lg">
