          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            Crack Repair and Targeted Solutions
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Not every water problem requires full-perimeter waterproofing. Isolated foundation cracks, window well leaks, or small sections of foundation wall can often be addressed with targeted repairs. Crack injection using polyurethane or epoxy costs $450-$850 per crack for interior injection, or $650-$1,200 per crack for exterior excavation and repair. These solutions work well for stable cracks in otherwise sound foundations.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Window well waterproofing costs $800-$2,200 per well including excavation, membrane application, proper drainage installation, and well reinstallation. Spot exterior waterproofing for small foundation sections (10-20 feet) ranges from $2,500-$5,500. These targeted approaches make sense when problems are truly isolated, but don't fall into the trap of repeated spot repairs when your foundation needs comprehensive waterproofing.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            Cost Factors That Increase Your Project Price
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Several factors push waterproofing costs above baseline estimates. Foundation depth is the primary driver — excavating to 10 feet costs substantially more than 8 feet due to additional soil removal, deeper membrane application, and increased material volumes. Difficult soil conditions, particularly clay in Woodbridge and Kleinburg, require more excavation time and potentially engineered solutions that add 15-25% to base costs.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Site access constraints significantly impact pricing. If excavators can't reach your foundation, contractors must hand-dig trenches at 3-4 times the cost of machine excavation. Existing landscaping, decks, or hardscaping that must be removed and restored adds $3,000-$12,000 depending on complexity. Tree protection for mature specimens near the foundation requires specialized techniques and monitoring that increase costs by $1,500-$4,000.
          </p>

