            Financing Your Waterproofing Project
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Basement waterproofing represents a significant investment that many Vaughan homeowners didn't anticipate. If Tarion won't cover your waterproofing needs or you've exceeded warranty periods, you'll need to fund the work privately. Home equity lines of credit (HELOCs) offer the most cost-effective financing, with interest rates 3-5% below unsecured loans and interest potentially tax-deductible when funding home improvements.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Some waterproofing contractors offer payment plans through third-party financing companies. These arrangements typically carry interest rates of 8-15% and should be compared carefully against HELOC or home equity loan options. If your waterproofing problem threatens your home's structural integrity or creates health hazards, consider it an emergency repair that justifies drawing on savings or emergency funds. Delaying essential waterproofing to avoid financing costs often results in far greater damage remediation expenses later.
