        <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-slate-900 mb-6">
          7. York Region Programs & Financial Assistance
        </h2>

        <div class="prose prose-slate max-w-none">
          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Several government programs and financial assistance options help Vaughan homeowners fund basement waterproofing projects. While these programs don't cover standard waterproofing costs, they may apply if your project includes energy efficiency improvements, environmental protection measures, or qualifies for emergency assistance. Understanding available programs helps you maximize available funding and reduce out-of-pocket costs.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            York Region Basement Flooding Protection Subsidy
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            York Region periodically offers subsidy programs for basement flooding protection measures. These programs typically cover 50% of eligible costs up to $3,200 for installing backwater valves, sump pumps, and related drainage improvements. While these subsidies don't fund full waterproofing projects, they help offset costs of critical flood protection components that should be part of comprehensive waterproofing.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Check York Region's website for current program availability. Funding is usually limited and allocated on a first-come, first-served basis. Applications require property assessment, quotes from licensed contractors, and proof that your property has experienced or is at risk of basement flooding. Woodbridge homeowners near the Humber River typically qualify more readily due to documented flood risk.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            Canada Greener Homes Grant
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            If your waterproofing project includes foundation insulation upgrades, you may qualify for Canada Greener Homes Grant funding. The program provides up to $5,000 for eligible home energy retrofits. Adding insulation to exterior foundation walls during waterproofing work creates minimal additional cost but can unlock grant funding that offsets a portion of your total project cost.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            The Greener Homes process requires pre- and post-retrofit energy evaluations by certified advisors (cost: $600-$800). These evaluations identify eligible improvements and verify completion. Foundation insulation typically qualifies when it increases your home's thermal resistance and reduces energy consumption. The grant application process takes 4-8 weeks, so plan accordingly if coordinating with waterproofing work.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-green-50 border-l-4 border-green-500 p-6 my-8 rounded-r-lg">
            <div class="flex items-start">
              <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-green-500 mr-3 flex-shrink-0 mt-1" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M12 8c-1.657 0-3 .895-3 2s1.343 2 3 2 3 .895 3 2-1.343 2-3 2m0-8c1.11 0 2.08.402 2.599 1M12 8V7m0 1v8m0 0v1m0-1c-1.11 0-2.08-.402-2.599-1M21 12a9 9 0 11-18 0 9 9 0 0118 0z" />
              </svg>
              <div>
                <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-green-900 mb-2">Stacking Incentives</h3>
                <p class="text-green-800">
                  Combining York Region flood protection subsidies with Greener Homes grants can reduce your waterproofing project cost by $5,000-$8,200. Coordinate timing carefully — complete subsidy applications before starting work, as most programs don't reimburse already-completed projects.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            Home Accessibility Tax Credit
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Ontario's Home Accessibility Tax Credit provides up to $1,500 annually for renovations that make homes more accessible for seniors or people with disabilities. If your waterproofing project includes accessibility improvements — such as grading adjustments that eliminate steps, or creating accessible basement access — a portion of costs may qualify. Consult a tax professional to determine eligibility before claiming this credit.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            Property Tax Rebates for Major Repairs
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Vaughan homeowners who complete major structural repairs including foundation work may qualify for temporary property tax relief during construction. This program doesn't provide direct funding but can reduce your property tax burden during the year you complete waterproofing work. Contact Vaughan's Tax Department to determine if your waterproofing project qualifies and how to apply for assessment adjustments.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            Insurance Coverage Considerations
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Standard home insurance doesn't cover gradual water damage or maintenance issues like failing waterproofing systems. However, if sudden events like pipe bursts or sewer backups caused your basement flooding, insurance may cover water damage remediation and potentially some waterproofing improvements. Review your policy carefully and document all damage with photos and professional assessments.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            After completing professional waterproofing, notify your insurance company. Many insurers offer premium reductions for homes with upgraded flood protection systems. Installing backwater valves, sump pumps with battery backup, and comprehensive exterior waterproofing can reduce your annual premiums by $150-$400 for Vaughan homeowners, particularly in flood-prone areas like Woodbridge.
          </p>

          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-slate-900 mb-4 mt-8">
            Emergency Financial Assistance
          </h3>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            If severe flooding has damaged your Vaughan home and you lack resources for immediate repairs, several emergency assistance options exist. The Canadian Red Cross provides emergency disaster assistance during major flooding events. York Region Community and Health Services offers emergency financial assistance for low-income residents facing housing emergencies. These programs have strict eligibility requirements but can provide critical support during crisis situations.
          </p>

          <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Local credit unions and community banks sometimes offer emergency home repair loans with more flexible approval criteria than major banks. These loans typically feature 5-7 year terms with interest rates of 6-10%. While more expensive than HELOCs, they provide access to funding when traditional financing isn't available.
          </p>
